<span class="header1">ARTS AND COMMUNICATIONS</span>
<p>Do you want to share your interest in nature and the environment
with others?  Do you have strong communication skills?  If so, a
career as an environmental lawyer, writer, or photographer may be of
interest to you.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Environmental Lawyer</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1360.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Environmental Lawyer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you want to influence how people and
organizations use the earth's environment, this occupation may be
for you. To practice environmental law, you must understand the law
and communicate well. You must also be organized and able to
negotiate with others. If you become an environmental lawyer, you
might develop a legal case or appear in court to prevent the
building of a road through a wilderness area.  You might also defend
a logging company's right to build that road.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You will need a bachelor's degree and three
years of law school to be an environmental lawyer. You must also
pass the state "bar exam."  To learn about nature sciences and city
and rural development, volunteer with political action groups
concerned about the environment.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of lawyers was $122,960
in May 2019.
</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Writer</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1040.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Writer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like to write and are good at it, you may
want to become a professional writer. Writers express their thoughts
and ideas through words written on a page or computer screen. As a
writer, you could help inform others about issues that affect the
environment. You may work on nature documentaries, or on articles
for newspapers, nature magazines, or scientific
journals.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employers look for writers with at least a
bachelor's degree. Education is very valuable, but you must have
talent and skill too. You will want to write as much as possible.
Getting involved in writing groups, school newspapers, and yearbooks
can give you valuable experience and improve your skills. Practice
is important, so take every opportunity to write.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of writers and authors
was $63,200 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Nature Photographer</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/43060.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" ALT="Nature Photographer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like taking pictures of natural settings
and have a good "eye,"  you may become a nature photographer. To do
so, you must be creative and understand how cameras work. Your work
might appear in magazines, books and journals, or in travel and
advertising displays. Many photographers work for themselves. So, it
is helpful to understand how a small business works.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A bachelor's degree in photography or the visual
arts can develop your basic skills. But, you also need to be
creative to succeed in this	field. Spend as much time as
possible looking at great pictures and taking your own. Getting
involved in photography clubs and working in photo shops and labs
will help you learn more about using your camera to capture
nature.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of photographers was
$36,280 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

<span class="header1">ANIMAL AND NATURE SCIENCES</span>
<p>Occupations in this field are concerned with studying and working
with plants and animals. They are more "hands on" than occupations
in the arts and communication field. People in this field work to
benefit the plants and animals in our environment. They should be
active and enjoy being in nature and working outdoors.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Botanist</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1020.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Botanist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Botanists (wildlife biologists) study plants and their environments.
Some study all aspects of plant life, including algae, fungi,
lichens, mosses, ferns, conifers, and flowering plants; others
specialize in areas such as identification and classification of
plants, the structure and function of plant parts, the biochemistry
of plant processes, the causes and cures of plant diseases, the
interaction of plants with other organisms and the environment, and
the geological record of plants.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
		<blockquote>Most biological scientists need a Ph.D.
degree
in biology or one of its subfields to work in research or
development positions. A period of postdoctoral work in the
laboratory of a senior researcher has become common for biological
scientists who intend to conduct research or teach at the university
level.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of botanists was $63,270
in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Zoologist</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AB/1079.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Zoologist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy learning about and working with
animals, you may become a zoologist.  Zoologists work in zoos and
wildlife parks.  They also work in research centers and agricultural
settings.  If you become a zoologist, you could help save animals or
protect endangered species. You might also help develop better ways
to raise animals for food, or work to produce better breeds of
animals.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A zoologist must have at least a bachelor's
degree for an entry-level job.  Employers prefer a master's degree
or Ph.D.  To find out if you enjoy close contact with animals, you
might work on a farm, or in a zoo or pet store.  You might also
volunteer as a veterinarian's assistant.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of zoologists was $63,270
in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Logging Worker</span>
	<br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Logging workers harvest timber from forests to
provide the raw material for consumer and industrial products.
Logging jobs are physically demanding and can be dangerous.  Workers
spend the majority of their time outdoors, sometimes in bad weather
and often in remote areas.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most logging workers need a high school
diploma.  You will recieve on-the-job training.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage for logging workers was
$41,230 in May 2019.</blockquote>

